{
  "terms": [
    {
      "term": "Atom",
      "simpleDefinition": "The basic building block of all matter, consisting of a central nucleus and orbiting electrons.",
      "anchor": "Think of it as the smallest possible 'lego brick' of a material.",
      "misconception": "Thinking atoms are solid balls; they are actually mostly empty space with particles moving inside."
    },
    {
      "term": "Nucleus",
      "simpleDefinition": "The central part of an atom containing protons (positive) and neutrons (neutral).",
      "anchor": "The 'sun' at the center of the atomic solar system.",
      "misconception": "Confusing the nucleus with the electrons that orbit around it."
    },
    {
      "term": "Electron",
      "simpleDefinition": "A tiny, negatively charged particle that orbits the nucleus of an atom.",
      "anchor": "The 'planets' orbiting the nucleus; their movement is what we call electricity.",
      "misconception": "Believing electrons are stationary; they are constantly in motion."
    },
    {
      "term": "Valence Shell",
      "simpleDefinition": "The outermost orbit or shell of an atom where electrons are located.",
      "anchor": "The 'outer fence' of the atom.",
      "misconception": "Assuming all shells are involved in electrical flow; only the outer shell determines conductivity."
    },
    {
      "term": "Free Electron",
      "simpleDefinition": "An electron in the outer shell that can easily break away and move to a neighboring atom.",
      "anchor": "A 'commuter' that can jump from one train station (atom) to the next.",
      "misconception": "Thinking all electrons in an atom are free to move; most are tightly locked in inner shells."
    },
    {
      "term": "Conductor",
      "simpleDefinition": "A material that has many free electrons, allowing electricity to flow through it easily.",
      "anchor": "Copper or aluminum wiring used in house circuits.",
      "misconception": "Thinking a material is a conductor by 'magic' rather than because of its atomic structure."
    },
    {
      "term": "Insulator",
      "simpleDefinition": "A material where electrons are tightly bound to their atoms and cannot move easily.",
      "anchor": "The plastic (PVC) coating on the outside of a cable.",
      "misconception": "Believing insulators have no electrons; they have plenty, but the electrons are 'locked' in place."
    }
  ],
  "anchorPhrases": [
    "Electricity is the movement of free electrons.",
    "Conductors have loosely bound outer electrons.",
    "Insulators hold their electrons in a tight grip.",
    "The valence shell is the key to electrical flow."
  ],
  "misconceptionTargets": [
    "Electricity is not a liquid; it is the flow of subatomic particles.",
    "Materials are classified by how easily their electrons can move, not just by what they are made of.",
    "An insulator does not 'block' electricity like a wall; it simply refuses to let its own electrons move."
  ]
}

{
  "teachChecks": [
    {
      "title": "Basic Electron Theory",
      "objective": "Explain the structure of the atom and the role of electrons in electrical flow.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "Every material you handle on-site, from copper cable to plastic trunking, is made of atoms. Think of an atom as a miniature solar system. At the center is the nucleus, which contains protons and neutrons. Orbiting this nucleus are tiny, negatively charged particles called electrons. These electrons sit in different layers or 'shells' at varying distances from the center.",
        "The most important part for an electrician is the valence shell, which is the outermost orbit of the atom. In some materials, the electrons in this outer shell are loosely held and can easily break away to move to a neighboring atom. We call these 'free electrons.'",
        "When these free electrons move in a coordinated direction through a material, that movement is exactly what we call electricity. It is not a liquid; it is the physical shifting of these subatomic particles from one atom to the next. Without this atomic movement, electrical current cannot exist."
      ],
      "hint": "Focus on the outermost shell and the specific name for electrons that can move between atoms."
    },
    {
      "title": "Conductors vs Insulators",
      "objective": "Differentiate between materials based on their electron availability.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "Materials are classified by how their atoms hold onto their electrons. A conductor is a material that has a large number of free electrons. In metals like copper, aluminum, or steel, the valence electrons are loosely bound, allowing them to drift easily from one atom to the next. This makes them ideal for wiring because they allow electricity to flow with ease.",
        "An insulator is the complete opposite. In materials like PVC, rubber, or glass, the electrons are held in a tight grip by the nucleus. There are virtually no free electrons available to move. It is a common misconception that insulators 'block' electricity like a wall; in reality, they simply refuse to let their own electrons move.",
        "This is why we use PVC to coat copper wires. The copper acts as the path for the flow, while the PVC insulator keeps the electrons contained within the cable. This prevents the electricity from escaping and causing a shock or a short circuit."
      ],
      "hint": "Think about which material has 'free' electrons and which material holds them in a 'tight grip'."
    }
  ]
}

{
  "teachChecks": [
    {
      "title": "Basic Electron Theory",
      "basicQuestions": [
        {
          "questionText": "What is the technical name for the outermost orbit or shell of an atom?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Valence shell",
            "The valence shell",
            "Outer shell",
            "Outermost orbit"
          ]
        },
        {
          "questionText": "What are the tiny, negatively charged particles that orbit the nucleus of an atom?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Electrons",
            "Electron",
            "Negative particles",
            "Orbiting particles"
          ]
        },
        {
          "questionText": "What term is used for electrons in the outer shell that can easily break away to a neighboring atom?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Free electrons",
            "Free electron",
            "Loosely held electrons",
            "Mobile electrons"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "deeperQuestionText": "Why is the physical movement of free electrons between atoms necessary for electricity to exist?",
      "deeperAnswerGuidance": [
        "Electricity is defined as the coordinated movement of subatomic particles",
        "Without the shifting of electrons from one atom to the next there is no flow",
        "Electricity is not a liquid but a physical movement of particles",
        "The movement of these particles is what constitutes an electrical current"
      ],
      "hint": "Focus on the name of the outermost shell and the specific type of electron that is able to move between atoms."
    },
    {
      "title": "Conductors vs Insulators",
      "basicQuestions": [
        {
          "questionText": "What classification is given to a material that has a large number of free electrons?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Conductor",
            "Conductive material",
            "Electrical conductor"
          ]
        },
        {
          "questionText": "What specific insulating material is commonly used to coat copper wiring to keep electrons contained?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "PVC",
            "Polyvinyl chloride",
            "Plastic coating",
            "PVC insulation"
          ]
        },
        {
          "questionText": "How does the nucleus of an insulator hold onto its electrons compared to a conductor?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Tight grip",
            "Tightly bound",
            "Firmly held",
            "Locked in place"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "deeperQuestionText": "Why is it technically more accurate to say an insulator refuses to let its own electrons move rather than saying it 'blocks' electricity?",
      "deeperAnswerGuidance": [
        "Insulators still contain electrons but they are not free to move",
        "The material lacks the free electrons required for flow",
        "It is an atomic property of the material rather than a physical wall",
        "The nucleus holds the electrons too tightly for them to drift between atoms"
      ],
      "hint": "Think about the difference between having 'free' electrons and having electrons held in a 'tight grip'."
    }
  ]
}

{
  "guidedPractice": {
    "title": "Guided Practice: Categorizing Site Materials",
    "objective": "Categorize common site materials into conductors or insulators based on their electron properties.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "On-site, you will encounter materials like Steel (used for conduit) and Rubber (used for flexible cable sheathing).",
      "To classify these, we apply the same logic used for Copper and PVC.",
      "Step 1: Identify if the material has 'free electrons' in the valence shell that can move easily.",
      "Step 2: Identify if the material holds its electrons in a 'tight grip' with no mobility.",
      "Step 3: Assign the technical classification based on that electron behavior."
    ],
    "questionText": "Classify both Steel and Rubber by describing the state of the electrons in their valence shells and their resulting material type.",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "Steel is a conductor because it has free electrons in its valence shell that can move.",
      "Rubber is an insulator because its electrons are held in a tight grip and cannot move easily."
    ],
    "hint": "Think about which material allows electrons to 'drift' and which one keeps them 'locked' in place."
  },
  "practice": {
    "title": "Practice: Defining Material Conductivity",
    "objective": "Validate the ability to define electron flow and distinguish material types using technical terminology.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "Aluminum is frequently used for overhead power lines and large distribution cables.",
      "To understand why it is chosen for this role, you must look at its atomic structure rather than just its appearance as a metal."
    ],
    "questionText": "Using the technical terms 'valence shell' and 'free electrons', explain why Aluminum is classified as a conductor.",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "Aluminum is a conductor because it has free electrons in its valence shell that are able to move from atom to atom."
    ],
    "hint": "Focus your answer on what is happening in the outermost shell of the Aluminum atom."
  }
}

{
  "integrative": {
    "title": "Integrative Close: The Atomic Basis of a Cable",
    "objective": "Synthesize the relationship between atomic structure and practical material selection in an electrical installation context.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "When you strip a standard PVC-insulated copper cable, you are looking at two materials with opposite atomic behaviors working together.",
      "To understand how this cable functions safely and effectively, you must look past the surface and consider what is happening in the valence shells of both the copper and the PVC."
    ],
    "questionText": "Explain the atomic difference between the copper core and the PVC insulation of a cable. Your answer must use the terms 'valence shell' and 'free electrons' to describe why one allows flow and the other prevents it.",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "Copper is a conductor because it has many 'free electrons' in its valence shell that can easily move from atom to atom to create electrical flow.",
      "PVC is an insulator because its electrons are held in a 'tight grip' within the valence shell and cannot move, which prevents the flow of electricity from escaping the cable."
    ],
    "hint": "Focus on which material allows electrons to 'drift' and which one keeps them 'locked' in place to ensure the cable is safe to handle."
  }
}

